PARAGRAPH.#text: Good morning. Sometimes a strong offense is the best defense, whether the antagonist is an organization trying to crash your Web servers, or Mother Nature crashing the shores of lower Manhattan. Bank of New York Mellon CIO Suresh Kumar says the bank invests a “meaningful percentage” of its $1.9 billion annual IT budget on technology that constantly replicates client and corporate data in real-time at a backup data center. This architecture, and other business continuity plans, allowed the bank to continue doing business without interruption throughout Hurricane Sandy and its aftermath. "All of the planning and investment we made certainly came in handy,” Kumar tells CIO Journal. Not every organization needs to adopt such aggressive -- and expensive -- business continuity systems, but the time to make that determination isn't during the middle of a hurricane, as Knight Capital learned a few weeks ago.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Download: CIOs Confronting Social Media
Headlines.Author: Michael Hickins
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Download: CIOs Confronting Social Media

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Good morning. The upcoming Facebook IPO is forcing CIOs to consider the unpredictable nature of social networks. Most CIOs of companies in unregulated industries have given in to the use of Facebook on the corporate network, but few have considered the explicit, if sometimes surprising benefits of social networking on business and employee behavior.
It turns out, for instance, that people tend to be more honest about their accomplishments on networks like LinkedIn -- which provide the social equivalent of peer review -- than they are on resumes they use in employment applications, as CIO Journal's Rachael King reports. Imagine how much trouble Yahoo would have been spared if the company had used the social network to vet the credentials of its embattled CEO, Scott Thompson.
Or consider an industry like insurance, where complex rules regulate -- but don't prohibit -- the use of social media. John Glooch, CIO of the Hartford Financial Insurance Company's life insurance unit, tells CIO Journal the rules are so complicated he's sworn off Facebook, even though social networks are an obvious and natural boon to selling in a business that relies so much on relationship-building. Clearly, it's worth their while for CIOs to work with their peers in legal and marketing to establish clear rules of the road for using these tools -- because we can assure you that your competitors are doing exactly that.
In reality, social media are like complex electronic systems with humans as unpredictable components. They can't be adequately governed by simplistic rules. This brings us neatly to a guest column for CIO Journal from former IBM executive Irving Wladawsky-Berger. He writes that we need to think about how individual components behave together in complex systems, rather than assuming that if each one is built to spec, they will all work together as expected. The simplicity of the industrial age doesn't work in complex systems like airplanes, electronic trading platforms -- not to mention social networks.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Download: CIOs Confronting Social Media

Cybersecurity experts joke that there are only two types of companies: those that know they've been hacked, and those that don't. Given the number of hands (and developers) that have touched all the components that go into building supposedly secure networks, there's also a good chance someone has planted a back door into your systems -- even if it's only for the purpose of "maintenance."
Sometimes the only way to ensure critical company data is kept away from prying eyes is to keep it offline. At the Bloomberg Cybersecurity Conference in New York yesterday, Johnson & Johnson chief of worldwide information security told us she sometimes resorts to this tactic. She later confided to a Booz Allen Hamilton executive present at the conference that she had to "just shut... down" a system she realized had been compromised.
